.TH BASE91 1 "February 2026" "BaseX 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
base91 \- base91 encode/decode data and print to standard output
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B base91
[\fIOPTION\fR]... [\fIFILE\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Base91 encode or decode FILE, or standard input, to standard output.
.PP
Base91 encoding uses variable-length encoding to achieve approximately
23% overhead, making it more efficient than Base64 (33%) and Base85 (25%).
This implementation includes CPU-specific optimizations (AVX2, BMI2)
for maximum performance on modern Intel and AMD processors.
.PP
With no FILE, or when FILE is \-, read standard input.
.PP
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-d, \-\-decode
Decode data
.TP
.B \-w, \-\-wrap=COLS
Wrap encoded lines after COLS characters (default 76).
Use 0 to disable line wrapping
.TP
.B \-i, \-\-ignore\-garbage
When decoding, ignore non\-alphabet characters
.TP
.B \-\-cpu\-info
Show detected CPU features and performance characteristics, then exit
.TP
.B \-\-help
Display help message and exit
.TP
.B \-\-version
Output version information and exit
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
.B Encode a file:
.RS
base91 input.txt > output.b91
.RE
.PP
.B Decode a file:
.RS
base91 \-d output.b91 > input.txt
.RE
.PP
.B Encode from stdin:
.RS
echo "Hello World" | base91
.RE
.PP
.B Check CPU optimizations:
.RS
base91 \-\-cpu\-info
.RE
.SH PERFORMANCE
On systems with AVX2 support (Intel Haswell and later, AMD Excavator and later),
base91 can achieve encoding speeds of 5\-8 GB/s. On older CPUs without SIMD support,
performance is approximately 1\-2 GB/s.
.PP
The tool automatically detects available CPU features at runtime and selects
the optimal code path.
.SH ALPHABET
Base91 uses the following 91-character alphabet:
.RS
A\-Z a\-z 0\-9 !#$%&()*+,\-./:;<=>?@[]^_`{|}~
.RE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Failure (invalid input, decoding error, etc.)
